I need to filter the tv_ratings dataset to only keep the shows that have 5 or more seasons.

tv_long <- tv_ratings |> 
  group_by(title) |> 
  summarise(num_seasons = n()) |> 
  ungroup() |> 
  left_join(tv_ratings, by = "title") 

tv_long <- tv_long |>  
  filter(num_seasons >= 5)

Now, I will make a line plot to trace how average ratings evolve across seasons.

ggplot(tv_long, 
       mapping = aes(x = seasonNumber, 
                     y = av_rating)) + 
    geom_line(aes(group=title))

The above line graph is very messy, but it is still clear that most shows hover around an average rating of 8, while some dip below a 7 and some rise above a 9 or 10.

Question 3

tv_good <- tv_ratings |>  
  filter(av_rating >= 9)

I filtered the original tv_ratings dataset to only include rows/seasons where the average rating was 9 or more.

Now I will make a barplot where the x-axis is genre.

ggplot(tv_good, 
       mapping = aes(x = genres)) + 
    geom_bar()

Since it is hard to read the genres on the x-axis, I will add the coord_flip() function to make it more legible. This function rotates the graph 90 degree clockwise so that instead of the bars going vertical, the bars are horizontal and the x-axis is to the left where the bars start. This enables us to read each genre next to each bar on the x-axis.

ggplot(tv_good, 
       mapping = aes(x = genres)) + 
    geom_bar() + 
    coord_flip()

The genre with the most top-rated shows is Drama with over 11 shows.

Question 4

Now I want to compare comedies and dramas in their average ratings. First, because the genres names are so convoluted, I am going to classify everything that includes the word âComedyâ as a comedy. I will make a new dataset called comedies_dramas that only includes those 2 genres.

comedies_dramas <- tv_ratings %>% 
  mutate(is_comedy = if_else(str_detect(genres, "Comedy"), 
                             1, 
                             0)) %>% # If it contains the word comedy then 1, else 0
  filter(is_comedy == 1 | genres == "Drama") %>% # Keep comedies and dramas
  mutate(genres = if_else(genres == "Drama", # Make it so that we only have those two genres
                          "Drama", 
                          "Comedy"))

Question 5

Now I will use the same data to make a histogram.

ggplot(comedies_dramas, 
       mapping = aes(x = av_rating, fill = genres)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(~genres)
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

The histogram provides the additional information that there are many more comedies than genres in total, which you are unable to see from the density graph. The histogram also displays the distribution of the average rating by genre, but has count on the y-axis instead of density/area.

Now I will use geom_freqpoly() with the same dataset to compare these different types of graphs.

ggplot(comedies_dramas, 
       mapping = aes(x = av_rating, color = genres)) +
  geom_freqpoly() 
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

After making the frequency poly graph, I notice that the distribution of the average rating for comedies is very similar to that for dramas, since I can see these 2 distributions layered on top of each other on one graph with the 2 lines. The comedy line starts to rise around a similar average rating that the drama line starts to rise, and same for when both lines start to fall back down to a count of 0.

Of the 3 plots, I think that the density graph, the 1st one, is most informative because it has density on the y-axis instead of count. When count is on the y-axis, it is easy to misinterpret the graph when there are so many more comedies than dramas, like in the histrogram and frequency poly graph. We are atttempting to compare the distribution of average rating among comedies with the distribution of average rating among dramas, not the count of each. Also, the distribution for each genre is plotted on the same graph so you can easily compare the pattern for each genre.

Question 6

ggplot(comedies_dramas, 
       mapping = aes(x = av_rating, 
                     y = share)) + 
  geom_bin_2d(bins = c(40, 40))

I see a graph with share on the y-axis and average rating on the x-axis with boxes displaying the count of shows that have the corresponding x and y value. Most of the shows center around an average rating of about 8 and a share value between 0 and 5. Compared to a scatterplot, I am able to avoid overplotting that would occur if the data were represented as dots instead of colored boxes. I can see that there are over 60 shows that have a rating slightly above 8 and a very low share value, but this would not be as clear on a scatterplot.

ggplot(comedies_dramas, 
       mapping = aes(x = av_rating, 
                     y = share, 
                     fill = genres)) + 
  geom_bin_2d(bins = c(40, 40))

After adding genres to the fill aesthetic, I am able to assess the distribution by genre. The patterns that I see are that comedies tend to have a higher share value compared to dramas overall, while both genres have a similar average rating distribution, centering around 8 with a few low outliers. However, the big outlier that apparently captured the nation with a share value of 27.24 was season 1 of the drama Dekalog in 1990.
